
1. Why do we split data into training and testing sets?

Training set teaches model patterns. Testing set measures generalization performance on unseen data, simulating production deployment.

Core Engineering Principle:

Training data → Model parameters (β coefficients)
Testing data → Unbiased performance estimate (R², accuracy)

Without separation → Overfitting guaranteed (model memorizes training examples).



2. What happens if we train and test on the same data?

Same data for training + testing produces artificially inflated metrics:

text
Training R²: 0.98 → Model "perfectly fits" training data
Testing R²:  0.98 → Same data, no new information

Reality (production): R² = 0.62 → Catastrophic failure

Failure Mechanism:

text
Model learns: "Record #47 has salary ₹25L" (memorization)
NOT: "5 years exp → ₹25L salary" (generalization)

Business Impact: ₹100Cr+ payroll errors from over-optimistic hiring models.



3. Explain the role of `test_size`.

test_size controls proportion of data reserved for unbiased evaluation:

python
# Industry standards
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, 
    test_size=0.20,      # 80/20 → Most common [web:850]
    random_state=42
)

Optimal Ratios by Dataset Size:

| Samples | test_size | Rationale             |
| ------- | --------- | --------------------- |
| 500-1K  | 0.30      | Limited data          |
| 1K-10K  | 0.20      | Production standard   |
| 10K+    | 0.15      | Statistical stability |

Constraint: test_size ≥ 0.10 (minimum statistical power).



4. Why is `random_state` important?

random_state fixes pseudo-random split seed for deterministic results:

python
# ❌ Different runs → Different splits → Inconsistent evaluation
X_train1, _, _, _ = train_test_split(X, y)
X_train2, _, _, _ = train_test_split(X, y)  # Different!

# ✅ Same split across runs → Fair model comparison
X_train1, _, _, _ = train_test_split(X, y, random_state=42)
X_train2, _, _, _ = train_test_split(X, y, random_state=42)  # Identical!

Production Requirements:

text
✅ random_state=42 (universal standard)
✅ Document seed in model card
✅ Reproducible across team members
✅ Git commit hash as fallback



5. When is Train–Test Split preferred over Cross Validation?

| Scenario              | Train-Test Split ✅        | Cross-Validation ✅         |
| --------------------- | ------------------------- | -------------------------- |
| Large datasets (>10K) | Fast baseline (30s)       | Statistical luxury (30min) |
| Rapid prototyping     | Single evaluation         | k× evaluations             |
| Production baseline   | Industry standard         | Hyperparameter tuning      |
| Small datasets (<1K)  | ❌ Insufficient test power | Robust estimate            |
| Time series           | Time-based split          | Walk-forward CV            |


